Myth: **The Perfect Route**

Years later, Lena and Iris met a young navigator obsessed with optimization.

"I've mapped seventeen routes to the northern port," she said, showing elaborate charts. "I'm calculating which saves the most time."

"How long have you been calculating?" Iris asked.

"Three weeks."

"And the journey takes?"

"Four days," the navigator admitted.

Lena nodded toward their own boat. "We use the coastal route. Takes five days, perfectly safe."

"But mine might take only four!" the navigator protested. "Maybe even three-and-a-half if the winds cooperate!"

"Might," Iris observed. "After three weeks of analysis, you still don't know."

"I'll figure it out! Optimization requires thoroughness!"

Lena and Iris sailed the familiar coastal route. Five days later, they returned with cargo sold.

The navigator was still calculating.

"You're wasting potential!" she called out.

"Maybe," Lena said, loading new cargo. "But we're earning actual coins, not theoretical ones."

"Don't you care about excellence?"

"We care about results," Iris replied. "Excellence in navigation isn't finding the absolute perfect route. It's reliably getting where you're going while you still have a reason to get there."

"That's settling," the navigator said.

"No," Lena smiled, sailing out again. "It's understanding that 'good enough, now' beats 'perfect, never.'"

The navigator kept calculating. They kept sailing.

