Myth: **The Calculated Loss**

Six months later, the young navigator finished her calculations.

"Finally!" she announced. "The optimal route—3.2 days to the northern port!"

She set sail immediately. The route required threading between shoals, catching precise tidal windows, trusting unusual currents.

Everything went perfectly. She arrived in 3.2 days, exactly as calculated.

The port master looked confused. "Where's your cargo?"

She stared at her empty boat. All her energy had gone to navigation—she'd forgotten to load anything.

When Lena and Iris arrived the next day on their familiar five-day route, they found her sitting on the dock.

"Your route worked," they observed.

"Perfectly," she said bitterly. "But I spent six months calculating it. Six months I could have made twenty trips on your 'good enough' route. Even accounting for the time saved per trip, I'm behind by... everything."

"The saddest calculations," Iris said gently, "are the ones that prove you optimized the wrong thing."

"I thought efficiency was everything."

"Efficiency serves purpose," Lena said. "When you forget the purpose, efficiency becomes just... motion."

